    <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
        <body>
            <div rend="parallel">
                <p xml:id="KT397-kilavi">varaiviṭai vaittu nīṅkun talaimakaṟkut tōḻi uraittatu. </p>


                <p xml:lang="en">Told by the confidante to HIM, who leaves [her],
                    after the time of marriage was fixed. </p>
            </div>

            <div rend="parallel">
                <lg xml:id="KT397">
                    <l> naṉaimutir ñāḻaṟ ciṉaimaru ṭiraḷvī</l>
                    <l> neytaṉ māmalarp peytal pōla</l>
                    <l> vūtai tūṟṟu muravunīrc cērppa</l>
                    <l> tāyuṭaṉ ṟalaikkuṅ kālaiyum vāyviṭ</l>
                    <l> ṭaṉṉā yeṉṉuṅ kuḻavi pōla</l>
                    <l> viṉṉā ceyiṉu miṉitutalai yaḷippiṉu</l>
                    <l> niṉvaraip piṉaḷeṉ ṟōḻi</l>
                    <l> taṉṉuṟu viḻumaṅ kaḷaiñarō vilaḷē.</l>


                </lg>

                <lg xml:lang="en">
                    <l> O man from the coast of the strong water, where the cold wind spreads</l>
                    <l rend="indent"> the egg-like <note place="foot">
                            <term xml:lang="ta">ciṉai maruḷ</term> : besides "twig", "egg" is a
                        further meaning of <term xml:lang="ta">ciṉai</term> ; and Cām. glosses <term xml:lang="ta">muṭṭaiyai pōṉṟa</term> . "Twig-like" does not seem to
                        make sense here.</note> round blossoms of the Ñāḻal,</l>
                    <l rend="indent8"> on which buds are ripening,</l>
                    <l rend="indent2"> on the big blossoms of the blue waterlily, as if raining:</l>
                    <l> like a child, which opens [its] mouth [and] calls “mummy”</l>
                    <l rend="indent"> even at a time, when the mother slaps [it] in quarrel,</l>
                    <l> whether you do what is unsweet or sweetly protect [her],</l>
                    <l> my friend [is] one with you as a border. <note place="foot">Here a
                        sentence-final particle is missing. It might be possible to read <term xml:lang="ta">varaippiṉaḷ</term> as a subject apposition to <term xml:lang="ta">tōḻi</term> , and <term xml:lang="ta">tōḻi </term> as
                        a subject to ilaḷē.</note>
                    </l>
                    <l> She doesn't have anyone to remove <note place="foot">How do we have to
                        understand the -ō on <term xml:lang="ta">kaḷaiñar-ō</term> ? Question and
                        answer would be possible: "one, who removes ...? She doesn't have [one]."</note>
                        the distress she has.</l>


                </lg>
            </div>
        </body>
